Weird cases: as impartial as a judge
Print
Share via
Facebook
Twitter
Google+
Gary Slapper
Published at 12:01AM, October 31 2013
When they take office, judges undertake to be fair and impartial. Being impartial means that a judge must not show bias towards either side of a case. Bias can manifest itself in various subtle ways, but it certainly includes an instance of a judge, while presiding, sending private text messages from the Bench to the prosecution giving secret tips on how that side should argue its case. That is why Judge Elizabeth E. Coker recently resigned from the Bench in Texas. In August 2012, Judge Coker was presiding in a trial of a man accused of violence against a child.
